{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412782"},"attributes":{"position":12,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"93"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480660"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"93"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261074"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":19,"questionsAnswered":7,"marksTotal":19,"marksAttainable":7,"marksAttempted":7,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:39:59+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.14,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"93","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/93"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.14,0.02,0.21,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"93"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77111"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"93","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/93"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"93"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62617"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2587"},{"type":"tags","id":"3421"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4056"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77111"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-month history of bloody diarrhoea and abdominal pain. She reports passing blood and mucus five to six times per day, with faecal urgency and tenesmus. She has experienced increasing fatigue. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has not travelled recently or taken antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 108/min, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There are several tender erythematous nodules on her anterior shins. Abdominal examination reveals mild generalised tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 100 g/L (115-165)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 13.0 x 10\u2079/L (3.6-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets 450 x 10\u2079/L (140-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EErythrocyte sedimentation rate 15 mm/hr (3-9)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPerinuclear anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA colonoscopy is arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following colonoscopic features would most likely be seen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythema, mucosal friability, granularity and ulceration","Granulomatous inflammation on histology","Pale mucosa with petechial bleeding","Transmural inflammation extending to muscularis","Melanotic pigmentation of colonic mucosa"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of ulcerative colitis including bloody diarrhoea, faecal urgency, tenesmus, and erythema nodosum. The presence of anaemia, leucocytosis, thrombocytosis, elevated inflammatory markers and positive perinuclear anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (p-ANCA) further support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema, mucosal friability, granularity and ulceration\u003C/strong\u003E are the characteristic colonoscopic findings in ulcerative colitis. These changes typically begin in the rectum and extend proximally in a continuous fashion. Histology shows inflammation limited to the mucosa and submucosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E with \u003Cstrong\u003Etransmural inflammation extending to muscularis\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of Crohn\u0027s disease. While Crohn\u0027s can present with bloody diarrhoea, it more commonly causes non-bloody diarrhoea and is less associated with p-ANCA positivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPale mucosa with petechial bleeding\u003C/strong\u003E suggests ischaemic colitis, typically seen in older patients with vascular disease or hypotension. This would not explain this young patient\u0027s chronic symptoms or elevated inflammatory markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanotic pigmentation\u003C/strong\u003E of colonic mucosa (melanosis coli) occurs with chronic laxative use. This would not explain this patient\u0027s presentation with bloody diarrhoea, systemic inflammation, and extraintestinal manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The inflammatory changes in ulcerative colitis are limited to the mucosal layers of the colon.","Colonoscopic features of ulcerative colitis include erythema, friability, granularity and ulceration in a continuous pattern.","Positive p-ANCA and extraintestinal manifestations like erythema nodosum support a diagnosis of ulcerative colitis over Crohn\u0027s disease."],"references":["Roozendaal C, Kallenberg CG. Are anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA) clinically useful in inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)? Clin Exp Immunol. 1999 May;116(2):206-13. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10337008/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62617"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"93"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62617"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T09:20:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T09:20:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"93"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77111"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda